		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=6606#comment-14165</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Not responding to e-mails until noon is great advice but difficult to do in today&#039;s corporate world.  I tried not responding until 10 a.m., but my boss received complaints that I was not responding quickly enough.  So, I had to go back to responding immediately.

The increasing volume of communication and the expectation of immediate response has created a workplace that emphasizes urgent tasks.  For many, the only time they have for important, longer term work is after business hours or on weekends.   

Although delaying response to e-mails until noon will be impossible for many, it is certainly worthwhile to try this or suggest this at work, perhaps on a more limited scale.  Most businesses could increase productivity greatly if even a small amount of uninterrupted time for important tasks were made available.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Not responding to e-mails until noon is great advice but difficult to do in today&#8217;s corporate world.  I tried not responding until 10 a.m., but my boss received complaints that I was not responding quickly enough.  So, I had to go back to responding immediately.</p>
<p>The increasing volume of communication and the expectation of immediate response has created a workplace that emphasizes urgent tasks.  For many, the only time they have for important, longer term work is after business hours or on weekends.   </p>
<p>Although delaying response to e-mails until noon will be impossible for many, it is certainly worthwhile to try this or suggest this at work, perhaps on a more limited scale.  Most businesses could increase productivity greatly if even a small amount of uninterrupted time for important tasks were made available.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
